","Of,, Kent, England":"Kent, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"about 1209–":"circa 1209–Overleden","1209–Male":"1209–Overleden","1211–1249":"1211–1249","1230–1298":"1230–1298","1241–Male":"1241–Overleden","1183–1215":"1183–1215","1185–1243":"1185–1243","1241":"1241","1230":"1230","Abt 1247":"circa 1247","1185":"1185","1183":"1183","1290":"1290","Abt 1241":"circa 1241","1315":"1315","1249":"1249","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","about 1209":"circa 1209","1224":"1224","1211":"1211","1243":"1243","1298":"1298","1209":"1209","about 1230":"circa 1230","1328":"1328","1317":"1317",", Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Fersfield, Norfolk, England":"Fersfield, Norfolk, England","Of,, Kent, England":"Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1209–":"about 1209–Deceased","1209–Male":"1209–Deceased","1211–1249":"1211–1249","1230–1298":"1230–1298","1241–Male":"1241–Deceased","1183–1215":"1183–1215","1185–1243":"1185–1243","1241":"1241","1230":"1230","Abt 1247":"about 1247","1185":"1185","1183":"1183","1290":"1290","Abt 1241":"about 1241","1315":"1315","1249":"1249","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","about 1209":"about 1209","1224":"1224","1211":"1211","1243":"1243","1298":"1298","1209":"1209","about 1230":"about 1230","1328":"1328","1317":"1317",", Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Fersfield, Norfolk, England":"Fersfield, Norfolk, England","Of,, Kent, England":"Kent, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bosco","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Salvatore, Carmine, Sal, Ignazio, Antonio, Attilio, Cosimo, Francesco, Gaspare, Luigi, Saverio.","Italian: topographic name for someone living or working in a wood, from <i>bosco</i> ‘wood’, from Late Latin <i>boscus</i> ‘shrub, undergrowth’ (of Gallic or ancient Germanic origin), or a habitational name from a place called with this word. In some cases it may have been an occupational name for a woodsman or forester and, by extension, a nickname for a surly or rough person. Compare   Lo Bosco  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Boschetti","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Mario, Angelina, Antonio, Guido, Rosario.","Italian: patronymic or plural form of a diminutive of   Bosco  ."]},{"name":"Lo Bosco","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Carmine, Gennaro, Sal, Salvatore, Antonino, Nichola, Pasquale, Piera, Raffaela, Rocco.","Italian (southern; also <b>Lobosco</b>): variant of   Bosco  , with the addition of the definite article <i>lo</i>."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"De","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":6,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705188,"age":15,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705189,"age":50,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705190,"age":81,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705191,"age":106,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705192,"age":119,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdicti